I read the reviews and I was really excited to arrange a dinner party for my family here. In my 61 years, I've eaten at thousands of restaurants all over the world, but never have I ever been so disappointed in what these crooks pull on their customers entry night. When the bill came, they applied a 10% service charge on top of the check. I asked the waiter what it was. There were only 4 of us, so I didn't think it was a waitperson tip? He told me that it wasn't. It was an undisclosed surcharge imposed by the management after the fact. In other words, they charge you the menu price of the food - plus another 10%! I asked him where in the menu it explained that. He said that it did not. So basically, they add 10% to your bill and don't tell you until the end of the meal when they bring the check. I asked a table of regulars nearby about it and they told me that it is the policy of the restaurant. If the Branzino on the menu was $22 instead of $20 - that would have been fine. I would make my decision with eyes wide open. But to tell me it was $20 and then charge me $22 - it's just theft. I'll never come here again.

GEORGIA 🇬🇪 Eat the World NYC review: A little past the midway point of Coney Island Avenue headed south, just before Midwood turns into Sheepshead Bay, quite a few options emerge for eating the cuisines of countries that made up the former Soviet Union. Even in Soviet times, the food of Georgia was one of the most beloved in the entire republic and much different than any other in the region. This year old restaurant is doing the full range of Georgian classics very well, our group of nine found hardly anything wanting after a big feast. Families and parties seem to be the main patrons on weekends, as massive trays of khinkali dumplings and cheesy baked breads showed up to greet them.

Bland:(((  Now, let me tell you the truth about what kind of food is REALLY served in this place...  But first, the positives: very tastefully done interior design, great service, average prices, no food poisoning post meal.  Now, off to food. We ordered many dishes and here's what was ok (not great, not wow) just edible: kharcho, khinkali, khachapuri. The Akropolice salad was really yummy. The liver cubes didn't have any life in them.  The only main dish we tried was the lamb stew with greens, I forget the name ch... something. It was atrocious! The meat was really cheap and wasn't really meat, but 70% fat. The stew was very bland with debris from the greens you had to spit out.  Overall, it's a shame that the chef managed to make Georgian food that was soulless, spiceless, and just simply boring. We will not be going back unless they step up their game.
